Title:
Small PIC Energy

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post explores “small PIC” (position-independent code) design for offensive agents, framed as a challenge: how much beacon/agent functionality can fit into ~4KB PIC without devolving into shellcode-golf.  
- It introduces updates around the Crystal Palace linker/composition workflow and Tradecraft Garden, including a Simple BOF runner, improved library merge behavior, and a new JSON-over-HTTP “Linker Sidecar” service for language-agnostic integration.  
- The core technical idea is separating “capability assembly” (building COFF modules, patching config, selecting features) from “tradecraft pairing” (turning COFF into PIC/shellcode and applying transformations like optimize/mutate).  
- It proposes “BOF inversions”: moving Beacon API implementation responsibility out of the C2 agent and into the BOF itself by merging a BOF API implementation during linking, then executing as a PICO with a minimal runner in the agent.  
- This enables “BOF cocktails” style pre-processing/evasion to be applied to BOFs independently of the C2, benefiting both research/detection experiments and operators who want self-protecting BOFs.  
- Useful for red team toolsmiths, C2 engineers, and tradecraft researchers building modular PIC agents, BOF pipelines, and low-friction integration into non-Java stacks.

Technical Focus:
- Position-independent code (PIC) minimization and modular agent design
- COFF/BOF to PIC/PICO transformation pipelines via spec-driven linking
- BOF inversions (embedding Beacon API implementations into BOFs)
- Tradecraft separation: capability build vs time-of-use transformations (+optimize/+mutate/ised)
- JSON-over-HTTP localhost sidecar API for linker automation/integration

Use Cases:
- Build ultra-small Windows PIC stagers/agents with modular features (e.g., WinINet loop + command kernel + BOF runner)
- Pre-process BOFs into self-contained PICOs that don’t require full Beacon API support in the agent
- Integrate Crystal Palace linking into custom C2 frameworks (Python/Go/Rust/etc.) via the sidecar service
- Run controlled experiments comparing “naked BOFs” vs tradecraft-paired BOFs for detection research
- Reduce agent complexity by delegating BOF API surface into link-time merged code

Keywords:
PIC, position-independent code, Crystal Palace, Tradecraft Garden, COFF, Beacon Object File, BOF, Beacon API, BOF cocktails, PICO, shellcode, WinINet, spec file, linker pipeline, +optimize, +mutate, ised, JSON-over-HTTP, sidecar service, localhost API